This paper deals with approximate inference in Bayesian networks, which is a common problem in machine learning and artificial intelligence. The use of variational approximation is a popular technique in this area, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with both discrete and continuous variables, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of iterative adjustment of variational parameters is a common technique in neural networks, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. The paper also deals with handling evidence, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with large cardinality discrete variables, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category.
